{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e4a374b4-8f3a-4012-a2c8-9b53c6213693","content":"It's a straightforward change. In your project file, either **remove** the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property or set it to `false`:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Remove or set to false: -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**What this does:**\n- `MSTest.Sdk` defaults to **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (the new runner). Setting `UseVSTest` to `true` was opting *out* of it.\n- Removing that property lets the default kick in.\n\n**Key differences to be aware of:**\n\n1. **CLI** — Use `dotnet test` as usual, but the output format changes slightly.\n2. **`dotnet test` flags** — Some VSTest-specific switches (e.g. `--logger`, `--filter`) now use a different syntax. Run `dotnet test --help` after migrating to see the new options.\n3. **`.runsettings`** — Still supported, but some VSTest-specific nodes may be ignored.\n4. **CI pipelines** — If you publish `.trx` files, add `<TestingPlatformCommandLineArguments>--report-trx</TestingPlatformCommandLineArguments>` to your project or pass `-- --report-trx` on the command line.\n\nThat's it — no package changes needed since `MSTest.Sdk` bundles everything.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"29c38994-f825-452b-be9a-a2433775f4a7","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"9824:1492A1:175631:1E7E9C:69FFD826"},"id":"094d1be3-6e4e-4c44-bef4-681f9f46b1fe","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:58:24.332Z","parentId":"c6851c51-76ec-490c-967b-69ef2bf220c2"}
